What levels of Eclipse/VE/EMF/GEF are you using.
In general, you should use the news group for these kind of install issues
news://news.eclipse.org/eclipse.tools.ve

Are you using SUSE Linux? Do you have a firewall?

If you are use SUSE, this is a known problem with SUSE. You need to go to the
etc/.hosts file and go
to the line:

::1    localhost localhost-ipv6 ...

and remove the localhost tag of it. Leave the rest of the line there and do not
change the line that says:

127.0.0.1    localhost

If it is not SUSE, then do you have a firewall? It says it can't create a socket
connection. There should be more in the .log file. Could you please attach that
to this defect. Thanks.

This is le last error in my .log file.
I've a firewall. This firewall is by default in Fedora Core 2.
I've tried to allow access from 127.0.0.1 to 127.0.0.1 but no result.
Is there any parameter to put into my firewall to permit socket creation ?
Or where can I find other information about this ?
Thanks a lot.

I'm sorry but I know nothing about Fedora. Do you have a Fedora expert you can
consult about this?

Could you please try executing the command :
"iptables -A INPUT --protocol tcp --source 127.0.0.1 -j ACCEPT;" 
to enable network traffic on the localhost/127.0.0.1 IP and let know if this
works for you?

Also I am going to start a discussion for this topic on the newsgroup so that
others can benefit.

Correction: 
Please try running the command "iptables -I INPUT --protocol tcp --source
127.0.0.1 -j ACCEPT".

The command in Comment #5
(https://bugs.eclipse.org/bugs/show_bug.cgi?id=78161#c5) was for appending the
rule at the end of all rules - something which might not work when previous
rules drop packets.

The above mentioned command puts a rule at the top of the rule list.

It's an error in my configuration.
I'm sorry.
It was the file containing the aliases / names of my computer.
I've corrected it and now, it's OK.
Sorry for this bug report.
